  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Shelter Solutions in Unfinished and damaged buildings and increased access to water supply and improved community sanitation in Rural Damascus</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to respond to essential needs for llife-sustaining shelter solutions for the most vulnerable IDP families and provision of basic WASH services in Dharet Artous, which hosts 15,000 IDPs. 
Medair proposes to increase the project scope to include the community of Madamiyet Elsham, Rural Damascus, which is made up of IDPs, returnees and residents.

 The project will reach  900  families with shelter/NFI interventions for the most vulnerable - those living in completely unfinished buildings 
 The project will also undertake 2 community level WASH projects - to increase water supply that currently barely reaches Sphere Standard and address a dire situation in community sanitation

The first targeted area is Dharet Artous, a marginalized suburb of Artous that is in fact an enclave geographically within Rural Damascus Governorate but administered by Quneitra Governorate due to the area of origin of the population and its IDPs. Needs were identified by SARC and the Quneitra Directorate of Water and have been verified by Medair through direct site visits for further assessment and collaboration with the local municipality and the Artous water unit. 

The additional proposed target area is Madamiyet Elsham, also within Rural Damascus. The area was militarily encircled / besieged until 2016 , sustaining heavy shelling during the period since 2012 and many houses are damaged. While officially now considered accessibleopen, in  practical terms it practically remains difficult to access (with several strict checkpoints). 


The total project is 615K USD of which 200K USD has been committed by Swiss Development Cooperation (SDC), an existing donor on other Medair Syria projects. The request to SHF for 415K will provide the co-funding that SDC require. 

To date Medair Syria have directly implemented infrastructure projects in primary healthcare clinics (belonging to Ministry of Health) in various districts of Rural Damascus, and have successfully undertaken urban water supply rehabilitation projects in Artous, Yabroud and have ongoing in other locations in Rural Damascus. These will be handed over to DoWSAA. This project will similarly be directly implemented by Medair. A previous water project in Artous was the basis for exposing the significant needs in the marginalised suburb of Dharet Artous.</narrative>
  </description>
